>>63494462
I would say to plot the story a bit differently. Instead of planning a course of action for each character, try to simply drop obstacles in front of them, and let them figure it out.
Think of it like playing a ttrpg. Get in your characters head, and ask what they would do in a certain circumstance.
For example
>An orc warrior and a halfling thief approach a bridge, which is guarded by a toll booth
>The characters are supposed to outwit the guard with a cunning plan, but this goes against the orcs character who would want to fight the guard, therefore it won't work
That's one way of plotting a scene, but the better way is
>The orc and halfling approach the bridge
>The halfling jokes about how easy the guard will be to trick
>The orc disagrees
>The characters argue about a solution
>The argument causes the guard to walk over and confront them
>The orc yells and is aggressive, intent on fighting
>The halfling sees this as a distraction, and ties the guards shoelaces together
>Fight occurs, but is over quickly and both characters run away giggling

The fight becomes easy due to clever (unintentional) tricks
Each character acted in character
There was naturally flowing inter character conflict, and external conflict

>Native tribes are anthro species native to North America.
I basically figured all that out to give a reason for the MC to be there

I've figured out that much to figure out why the MC is there, he's sent by the English to plot a potential route for a trans-continental railroad, but I'm struggling to figure out why he takes that job, what his opinions and experiences with anthros are.

Unrelated: muzzle loader shootouts were metal as fuck because they were basically melee with extra steps. If you had a rifle, you were basically a spearman who had one shot to get off before closing to melee. If you had a pistol, you would almost definitely have a dedicated melee weapon as well. In fact, this is why armies at the time fired by ranks (or fired by files if they were in a loose formation.). It was to be able to blast apart an enemy charge. That, or all the ranks would fire at once before just straight charging in.

>Why he takes that job

Well, you have a setting. You have a main character. You have a secondary character. You have an objective for the MC. All that you need now is conflict.
>Savage natives
>Dwindling supplies
>Mud getting the carts stuck
>Impossible terrain
>Local fauna
>Bandits
>Rival companies/ nations on the same mission
>Incompetent leadership
>Illness
>Getting lost
So many opportunities for obstacles! You don't even need to plan them in advance. Straight up roll them on a chart, and have your character come up on them and say "oh fuck, how do I deal with this?". (But have the issue tie into the larger story obviously).
Grab yourself some conflict, throw it at your characters from time to time in between elaborate scenic descriptions, dialogue, and progressive action, and voila! You got a story.
